This paper discusses the use of negative acknowledgments (NACKs) in Information-Centric Networking (ICN), which is a subfield of computer networking (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the security implications of using NACKs, which falls under the subfield of computer security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses the design requirements and implications of NACKs, which could fall under the subfields of distributed computing (cs.DC) and systems and control (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses potential countermeasures to attacks related to NACKs, which could fall under the subfield of information theory (cs.IT).
